ce:section.ce:para:
Small molecules such as thiols, glucose, and reactive oxygen species that play vital roles in biological systems have also been documented to be successfully detected using a variety of C-dots prepared by different precursors and methods. Similar to anion sensing using C-dots, the detection of small molecules is also based on the recovery of C-dot fluorescence previously quenched by metal ions or metal NPs. The analytes can change the C-dot fluorescence intensity through binding the quenchers to release C-dots from C-dot/quencher complexes. A typical example is presented by Huang et al., where the Fe3+ quenched fluorescence of C-dots is recovered by phytic acid (PA) due to the stronger affinity of Fe3+ to PA than to carboxyl and/or aromatic hydroxyl groups (Fig. 5.12
                     ) [103]. The similar fluorescence off-on systems such as (C-dots-Pb2+) [89] and (C-dots-Cr2O7
                     2−) [90] have also been successfully demonstrated for sensing pyrophosphate and ascorbic acid, respectively.
